ed hard, nodded, shot one last glare at Will, and followed his father back into the library, slamming the door shut behind them.\x{201c}Well,\x{201d} said Jem after the door had closed behind Gabriel. \x{201c}That was about as bad as I had expected it would be. Is this the first time you\x{2019}ve seen him since last year\x{2019}s Christmas party?\x{201d} he asked, addressing the question to Will.\x{201c}Yes,\x{201d} said Will. \x{201c}Do you think I should have told him I missed him?\x{201d}\x{201c}No,\x{201d} said Jem.\x{201c}Is he always like that?\x{201d} Tessa asked. \x{201c}So awful?\x{201d}\x{201c}You should see his older brother,\x{201d} said Jem. \x{201c}Makes Gabriel look sweeter than gingerbread. Hates Will even more than Gabriel, too, if that\x{2019}s possible.\x{201d}Will grinned at that, then turned and began making his way down the corridor, whistling as he went. After a moment\x{2019}s hesitation, Jem went after him, gesturing for Tessa to follow.\x{201c}Why would Gabriel Lightwood hate you, Will?\x{201d} Tessa asked as they went. \x{201c}What did you do to him?\x{201d}\x{201c}It wasn\x{2019}t anything I did to him,\x{201d} Will said, stalking along at a rapid pace. \x{201c}It was something I did to his sister.\x{201d}Tessa looked sideways at Jem, who shrugged. \x{201c}Where there\x{2019}s our Will, there\x{2019}s a half-dozen angry girls claiming he\x{2019}s compromised their virtue.\x{201d}\x{201c}Did you?\x{201d} Tessa asked, hurrying to keep up with the boys. There was simply only so fast you could walk in heavy skirts that swished around your ankles as you went. The delivery of dresses from Bond Street had come the day before, and she was only just beginning to get used to wearing such expensive stuff. She remembered the light dresses she\x{2019}d worn as a little girl, when she\x{2019}d been able to run up to her brother, kick him in the ankle, and dart away without him being able to catch her. She wondered briefly what would happen if she tried to do that to Will. She doubted it would work out to her advantage, though the thought had a certain appeal. \x{201c}Compromise her virtue, I mean.\x{201d}\x{201c}You have a lot of questions,\x{201d} Will said, veering sharply to the left and up a set of narrow stairs. \x{201c}Don\x{2019}t you?\x{201d}\x{201c}I do,\x{201d} Tessa said, the heels of her boots clicking loudly on the stone steps as she followed Will upward. \x{201c}What\x{2019}s parabatai? And what did you mean about Gabriel\x{2019}s father being a disgrace to Shadowhunters?\x{201d}\x{201c}Parabatai in Greek is just a term for a soldier paired with a chariot driver,\x{201d} said Jem, \x{201c}but when Nephilim say it, we mean a matched team of warriors\x{2014}two men who swear to protect each other and guard each other\x{2019}s backs.\x{201d}\x{201c}Men?\x{201d} said Tessa. \x{201c}There couldn\x{2019}t be a team of women, or a woman and a man?\x{201d}\x{201c}I thought you said women didn\x{2019}t have bloodlust,\x{201d} Will said without turning around. \x{201c}And as for Gabriel\x{2019}s father, let\x{2019}s say that he has something of a reputation for liking demons and Downworlders more than he should. I would be surprised if some of the elder Lightwood\x{2019}s nocturnal visits to certain houses in Shadwell haven\x{2019}t left him with a nasty case of demon pox.\x{201d}\x{201c}Demon pox?\x{201d} Tessa was horrified and fascinated at the same time.\x{201c}He\x{2019}s made that up,\x{201d} Jem hastily reassured her. \x{201c}Really, Will. How many times do we have to tell you there\x{2019}s no such thing as demon pox?\x{201d}Will had stopped in front of a narrow door at a bend in the staircase. \x{201c}I think this is it,\x{201d} he said, half to himself, and jiggled the knob. When nothing happened, he took his stele out of his jacket and scrawled a black Mark on the door. It swung open, with a puff of dust. \x{201c}This ought to be a storeroom.\x{201d}Jem followed him inside, and after a moment so d